text:
this interview with the minds behind #victoriassecret is … really something⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
hours before @victoriassecret’s annual runway extravaganza, which is scheduled to take place on thursday night in new york city, @voguemagazine published an online interview with two of the lingerie brand’s “chief architects,” #edrazek and #monicamitro. the resulting conversation, moderated by @voguerunway director @nicolephelps, covered topics such as representation, #metoo, and the brand’s competitors. needless to say, it was a lot to take in.⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
“victoria’s secret gets credit for being a conversation starter, but the brand is not part of the evolving discussion around size diversity now,” wrote phelps in her introduction, citing brands like @universalstandard, @thirdlove, and rihanna’s @savagexfenty, which have become popular in part for promoting size, gender, racial, and ethnic diversity. “in many ways, the discussion around victoria’s secret is not about who it’s letting in,” phelps added. “but who it’s still keeping out.”⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
despite the flaws phelps describes, victoria’s secret is still hugely popular around the world. last year’s show, which was filmed in shanghai, china, attracted 1.6 billion eyeballs in 190 countries. razek and mitro go on to defend these numbers in the #vogue interview, as well as the brand’s relevancy and purpose … like a lot.⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
“i feel like our runways have been culturally diverse for a long time and that we’ve always celebrated our models’ backgrounds,” said mitro.⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
razek, meanwhile, seemed more intent on addressing the “haters,” saying that competitors and writers “carp” on the company because it’s so enormously successful.⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀
in that spirit, here are some lines that stood out to us from the interview. we’ll let them speak for themselves.
•••

text_retweet:
wszystko swietnie, lepiej późno niż wcale, ale czy to znaczy, ze ty, fajna, niegłupia babka, która ma sporo do powiedzenia, tutaj byłaś wynajęta kukiełka? kurczę, czy nikt nie widział, co się odwala na planie? rok po #metoo?  kiedy cały świat, także ten medialny, mówi od miesięcy wprost, ze to głównie media spierdolily edukacje ludzi w kwestii seksizmu, molestowania, mobbingu, praw mniejszości i tolerancji? aga, jesteśmy obie z tvn, z miejsca, gdzie pracował durczok, byłaś na czarnym marszu, walczysz o prawa kobiet i teraz przykro? bo się mleko rozlało? bo jest słuszny wkurw? bo paru uczestników celebryckich dało chamsko czadu na wyjeździe? i na szczęście dziennikarze, na szczęście tacy są, po tym jak zebrali po emisji szczęki z podłogi, postanowili powiedzieć głośno, ze coś tu jest nie tak? i za to spotkał ich hejt? bo tknęli nietykalnych? co tu się odwala? widziałam ten odcinek. było mi wstyd.

#repost from @aga_wozniak_starak. wstyd mi za 10. odcinek programu ameryka express. mimo, że jest to fantastyczny format, w którym oglądamy nie tylko zmagania uczestników, ale również najpiękniejsze zakątki świata i w luźnej, rozrywkowej formie staramy się przybliżyć inne kultury, to zadania przed którymi stawiani są nasi bohaterowie często budzą również moje wątpliwości. nie biorę udziału w pracach produkcyjnych przy wyborze konkurencji dla uczestników, nie jestem również świadkiem wszystkich zmagań na planie, nie jest to jednak żadnym usprawiedliwieniem, ponieważ jako prowadząca firmuję ten format własną twarzą. i dlatego dziś z przykrością stawiam sobie pytanie, czy powinnam ten program nadal prowadzić? przyjmuję wszystkie zarzuty, zgadzam się z nimi i ze swojej strony mogę powiedzieć jedynie przepraszam.
name: karolina korwin piotrowska

text: a recent visit from my mom drew my attention to this magnet. a gift from someone a long time ago. the irony being that the gift giver tried desperately to stamp down my strength, my passion and my confidence. he verbally assaulted me, abused and threatened me, gaslit me and eventually (thankfully) left me. it was the beginning of a new life and i was stronger, bolder and an abuse survivor. if i had not been through that i would not be as assertive and driven as i am today for women’s rights, social justice, equality, and fair play. i think i’m very well behaved😊 and just in time — women’s voices are needed more than ever right now! #feministdestiny #feminism #feminist #feministquotes #quotes #equality #speakupspeakout #neverthelessshepersisted #timesup #persisterhood #metoo #womenempowerment

text:
if your male friends, colleagues, family members etc are saying they’re scared now because of the me too movement, you just learned something new about them.
why would a man be scared of a movement that’s here to help all sexual assault and rape survivors speak out about their abuse, unless he himself has something to hide? unless he’s guilty of doing something? unless he’s one of those men who would sexually harass or rape someone?
the whole point is so that men stop physically, verbally and/or sexually harassing women like they still do way too often. if you’re too scared to “touch women” now, good. no woman wants to be fucking touched if she didn’t give you her fucking consent. it’s assault.
most of these men like to pretend they don’t understand how they’re assaulting a woman, until another man does the same thing that he’s doing, to him. very different when the tables are switched around, huh?
and for all the men now “too scared to talk to women”, you’re just telling everyone that you have no sense of how to be respectful to women. you either constantly harass them and think it’s ok, or you just “don’t know how to treat women properly.” which is the poorest excuse in the book.
i mean, what human being doesn’t know how to treat another human being correctly??
women are not your property. they’re not open to be felt up and touched, or harassed by you because you think you’re way too irresistible to resist.
women don’t like to be catcalled, whistled at, winked at, touched, perved on, watched, stared at, followed or nagged. none of these things are “compliments.” most of them, are what make women scared of men. plus the fact that there’s a high chance of her getting beaten, murdered or raped by a man sometime in her life.
scared of the me too movement? thanks for telling us who you really are.

text:
(guarda il video link in bio)
tempo fa in occasione di un evento di consapevolmente (https://m.facebook.com/consapevolmente.fi/?ref=bookmarks) dal titolo “forti, determinate, coraggiose: donne” preparai una videoclip introduttiva. la canzone guida del video era “bitch” di meredith brooks. niente di meglio per cantare la bellezza, la complessità ma anche la diversità che contraddistingue il mondo, in questo caso femminile. ad accompagnare la musica una carrellata di immagini di donne famose che hanno fatto la differenza nella società facendo, anche, da apripista sui percorsi battutti solo dagli uomini. riconosco che, per quanto semplice, questo video suscita una grande emozione. mi sono trovata a pensare, poi, che le donne che fanno la differenza non sono solo quelle famose, ce ne sono milioni là fuori che ogni giorno con coraggio, fatica oppure con spontaneità e leggerezza allargano “il campo d’azione” del femminile, dando la possibilità a tutte le donne di sentirsi tali con qualunque caratteristica. e’ nata così l’idea di questo video. e’ stata l’occasione per conoscere persone fantastiche, scambiarci esperienze e dare spazio ad un’energia travolgente che è quella che sprigioniamo quando ci sentiamo perfettamente noi stesse. la speranza è che questo video possa essere fonte di ispirazione per una, cento, un milione di donne.
rispondendo alla domanda di una mia amica “nel xxi secolo ancora ci sono donne che non si sentono libere?” dico che finché ci sarà anche solo una bambina, una ragazza, una donna che rinuncerà ad essere se stessa a causa dei pregiudizi di genere ci sarà qualcosa da cambiare nella società.
grazie alle protagoniste del video per essersi messe in gioco, ai miei amici di consapevolmente perché quello che facciamo è importante, grazie alle curandaie che ci hanno offerto un’accogliente location e perché ogni giorno offrono sostegno pratico alle donne (e non solo).
buona visione.

bibbablog

porriga trosor med hål i, olika outfits män sett i porr. jag hade en morakniv gömd under kudden, ifall en torsk skulle gå över gränsen. min säng hade lådor under sig som svämmade över av kondomer, dagen-efter-piller, sexleksaker, smärtstillande, krispiga gamla servetter med sperma på. där fanns också en liten bok som jag skrev ner mina tankar i, som jag skrev ner allt jag visste om männens identiteter i. jag tvingades pga mitt missbruk träffa män som min hallick inte visste jag träffade, jag behövde mer pengar än han krävde pga knark. så jag klev helt in i rollen, den lyckliga horan, tog på mig nätstrumpbyxor, leopardpälsjacka och pumps och gick på gatan. min enda tröst och mitt enda ljus var snön. alltså kokainet. jag hade en brinnande vrede jag inte kunde visa upp och en glöd som ingen man kunde fimpa. när morgonen närmade sig var jag fortfarande vaken. jag sålde sex dygnet runt. jag var aldrig less. jag varken kunde eller fick. när jag blev ”påkommen” med att sälja sex nämnde jag ingen hallick. jag var pressad från alla håll och jag valde att vara en lycklig hora. jag upplevde att knarket gjorde mig lycklig och att priset för det - min kropp - inte var högt. jag sammanblandade inte mig själv med rollen, det blev uppenbart i samtal med kuratorer. men däremellan var jag en avstängd, lycklig, påverkad och uppklädd hora. som inte var less. som bara körde på. det är först sen jag slutat knarka som jag kunnat va less. det är först när jag inte har nån hallick eller drogskuld som jag kan va less. det är därför jag skriver här. jag har aldrig glömt bort mig själv, jag har bara inte kunnat vara mig själv. och jag är så less! #metoo #prostitution #utanskyddsnät #intedinhora

text:
why  #metoo ?

i have been keeping it inside me for too long,
for when you did it you felt it was no wrong.
oh! we were friends before that grisly bit,
and  i trusted you and it was like bees and mint.
the air was filled  with a merry tattle,
before you held me and gave me a gratuitous cuddle.
i pushed you and said ," it isn't right",
you holding me wasn't pleasant but an uninvite.
with the least of regrets , you left,
and  then the onus was on me to reflect.
no, it's not a put on to make a mockery of you,
it's just me reaching out to other sisters who have suffered too.
and also this is why #metoo.

poet - @ggwizard98

as per reports, she was travelling with her family in the general compartment of punjab-bihar-jallianwala express on friday night when this shocking incident took place. 
where is human anger and intolerance leading our country to? was it because chinat was a woman, hence weak, that the assailant took her for granted?

text:
🙏🏿🙏🏿🙏🏿 while i respect what #metoo is trying to do, we should also remember those men who are falsely accused and had their livelihoods taken away unjustly or even their lives! case in point is this young brother right here that should still be alive right now. a woman he rejected lied to two gangbangers that he raped her, as a result, merlin santana was killed for no reason! and not that i feel sorry for them, but the two guys are in jail for life while the woman, who was under age at the time, got a slap on the wrist and only served until she was 18. everyone talks about tupac‘s death but i feel even more for merlin santana because he did absolutely nothing to deserve it!

so for you crusaders who are pursuing justice for women that have been raped, and it is an admirable thing you’re doing, remember guys like this who have been lied on by women. due process for all! or at least get your facts straight!

rest in peace merlin santana.

text: when a person experiences any sort of  trauma (sexual abuse, divorce, death, domestic violence, domestic abuse, abandonment, or emotional abuse) their self-esteem is impacted.  shame, and blame are just a few of the emotions that debilitates, and impacts their ability to achieve true happiness. working on self from the inside out is an essential part of recovery, and healing. as a supporter of survivors, we must work together to help them know their own mind, how to honor and care for their bodies, let them be aware of their capabilities, allow them to know they’re not perfect, but they’re good enough just as they are, identify their strengths and concentrate on what they can do instead of what they can’t, and most importantly tell them and yourself that you’re loved, beautiful, courageous, and simply fantastic! #buddyspeaks #selfesteem #mirror #boys #girls #trauma #happiness #metoo  #endchildhoodsexualabuse #divorce #teens #tweens
name: Buddy Speaks

text_retweet:
#repost @facesofbengaluru with @get_repost
・・・
“i was molested multiple times. by my own cousin when i was only 8. when i finally reported it to my family, all my aunts came to his defence saying, ‘we did not bring up our boy like that. you must have misunderstood his playfulness.’ i’m not sure how someone would playfully grope you or ‘accidentally’ touch your genitals for an awfully long time."
.
"he obviously grew up to become the guy who was yelled at for no reason, and i became the attention-seeking girl who wasn’t brought up well by her parents because she boldly spoke of things of sexual nature. he still is very much a part of the family gatherings and they wonder why i don’t meet them anymore.”
.
“i was 17 when i said yes to a 24-year-old. he was a jerk who told me often that i was an ‘average looking woman’ and he chose me among all the better-looking women who had asked him out because ‘hot women are usually slutty and don’t listen to their boyfriends’. so he wanted an average looking girl who’d know her limits and would remain ‘sanskari’."
.
"it was partly my fault. i like partying, i liked wearing dresses, i liked going on trips and breaking the rules. but i would try to suppress these desires because i also endorsed these sanskari stereotypes then. it got worse when he’d tell me not to talk to my male classmates or dress up in a skirt ‘provoking other men’. he’d tell me i had a psychological illness where i was desperate to show skin and that ‘some women have these issues’.”
.
"he’d forced himself upon me. yes, we were kissing. but that’s all i had consented for. and he forced himself upon me. he asked me if i was a virgin because he did not like ‘second-hand women’. he physically abused me in broad daylight one day. he didn’t want me meeting an old school guy-friend. he called me to a place nearby and thrashed me while people watched.  his dad feared i’d report him so he called and told me, ‘it is your fault. any man doesn’t like his girlfriend not obeying him’.
.
(1/2)

organizations call her to solve problems in extreme places and spaces. meet gabby almon on nov 14th, founder of @riseofthebulls : a changemaker network and laboratory, meeting the challenges of our times with creativity, imagination, and inspiration.
.
.
for the past decade, gabby served as a trusted advisor to fortune 500 companies, domestic and international governments, and numerous humanitarian organizations around the world. she’s helped these organizations prepare for and respond to large-scale emergencies and terrorist attacks. (the kind of events that become breaking news on tv and worst-case scenarios that keep leadership up at night.) .
.
.
.
new and emerging threats are going to require more big and creative thinkers to solve them. and she can help develop that talent.
.
.
.
savoir social hour is a time where we’ll aim to uncover the journey of the “wild woman.” this 3-part panel discussion will feature & uncover the secrets of our favorite “wild women.” conversations will be led by food & travel expert and founder of salt & wind, aida mollenkamp. she lives at the intersection of food and travel and everything aida does is driven by passion and creativity. during this series, aida will help each panelist discuss the literal and figurative journeys she embarked upon to harness the intuition that led her to become a “wild woman.”
.
.
.
part 3: wild women: visionaries becoming the voice- as if women aren’t doing enough, this stellar panel will feature women in activism, changemakers & social entrepreneurs. we’ll get to hear how these women are leading and taking charge for the greater good of all humanity!
.
.

.

text:
*credits unknown*

real rape doesn’t have to be committed by a stranger. a staggering 80%* of rapes are carried out by someone you know. that means that your assailant is your husband, boyfriend, friend, relative or co-worker. the authorities call it acquaintance rape, but its real rape, plain and simple. your attacker will know you and everything about you. they’ll know what to say and do to get what they want. some might say this kind of rape isn’t as bad, since you know your rapist, but that’s a load of you-know-what. studies show that rape by an acquaintance has more far-reaching psychological effects and symptoms than stranger rape. i mean, just imagine it. someone you love or care about, committing such a heinous act upon you against your will. how can that not mess you up?

text:
if you are experiencing harassment at work the first thing you should do is keep a record.
make a note of the incident(s) and if anyone else was present make a note of who witnessed the incident, as well as what time it was, where it was, what was said/done.
should you need to report the incident these notes will help you.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
a student from the missouri state university (msu) has been charged for allegedly raping a woman hours after she attended a #metoo rally in springfield over the weekend. according to a report by the , zachary alperin, 22, went to some bars with the victim after the rally ended, and then went to the woman’s room on campus, per the court documents.
in her statement, the victim said that she allowed zachary to sleep in her room but told him not to touch her because she was drunk, the springfield news-leader reported. the woman told police that she fell asleep and woke up to find alperin lying naked on top of her. per the springfield news-leader, the woman “alleged that alperin performed sex acts on her and she pushed him away.”
alperin allegedly confessed to performing sexual acts on the victim, as reported by the springfield news-leader. “i guess i tried to force myself on her, and i feel like such a terrible person for it,” the culprit told police. alperin is currently being held at the greene county jail on a bond of $20,000 following the investigation. he has been charged with second-degree rape and second-degree sodomy.
according to state law, if someone is convicted of rape and sodomy in the second degree, they can incur a maximum imprisonment of seven years, along with fines up to $10,000 for each offence. following the news, organizers of the #metoo rally in springfield expressed their shock at the incident and said that they have been “devastated” by the news. however, they appreciated that the victim mustered the courage to report the rape, a report by said.
“we are devastated. the thought that someone would leave our rally feeling so encouraged, just to be raped a few hours later… it is almost too much,” the organizers wrote in a facebook post, as quoted by nbc news. “if the woman who attended our rally that the article is referring to sees this, please know this: we are so proud of you for your bravery in coming forward. we are so sorry. we believe you. this was not your fault in any way. we are here for you,” it further read.

text:
our deepest fear
by marianne williamson

our deepest fear is not that we are inadequate. 
our deepest fear is that we are powerful beyond measure. 
it is our light, not our darkness
that most frightens us.

we ask ourselves
who am i to be brilliant, gorgeous, talented, fabulous?
actually, who are you not to be? 
you are a child of god.

your playing small 
does not serve the world. 
there's nothing enlightened about shrinking 
so that other people won't feel insecure around you.

we are all meant to shine, 
as children do. 
we were born to make manifest 
the glory of god that is within us.

it's not just in some of us; 
it's in everyone.

and as we let our own light shine, 
we unconsciously give other people permission to do the same. 
as we're liberated from our own fear, 
our presence automatically liberates others.

join us today for the second annual #metoo survivors' march at hollywood and highland!
.
➡schedule
12-1pm opening speeches and performances
1-2pm we march 💥
2-3pm closing speeches and performances
.
me too march international is holding space today for the victims of the woolsey fire currently raging throughout ventura and los angeles counties, and the victims of the recent shooting at the borderline bar in thousand oaks. the victims are members of our communities. we recognize that the changing environmental conditions have caused disasters such as the fires to become increasingly worse and me too march international stands with all victims of natural disaster and climate change, recognizing that mass movement of people can often result in chaotic scenarios where people are victimized in various ways. in addition, me too march international recognizes that lax gun laws and lapses in mental health care have led to thousands of unnecessary gun deaths each year, and me too march international supports all efforts to expand mental health support.
.
today, we ask attendees to carry a white rose while we march, in order to symbolize our solidarity with the victims and our hope for a better future.
.
.
.
.

text: when a person experiences any sort of  trauma (sexual abuse, divorce, death, domestic violence, domestic abuse, abandonment, or emotional abuse) their self-esteem is impacted.  shame, and blame are just a few of the emotions that debilitates, and impacts their ability to achieve true happiness. working on self from the inside out is an essential part of recovery, and healing. as a supporter of survivors, we must work together to help them know their own mind, how to honor and care for their bodies, let them be aware of their capabilities, allow them to know they’re not perfect, but they’re good enough just as they are, identify their strengths and concentrate on what they can do instead of what they can’t, and most importantly tell them and yourself that you’re loved, beautiful, courageous, and simply fantastic! #buddyspeaks #selfesteem #mirror #boys #girls #trauma #happiness #metoo  #endchildhoodsexualabuse #divorce #teens #tweens

text:
this picture is about an incident that happened on october 23.
on october 23, tamil nadu woke up to something that should've stunned it to shame. there is a village called thalavaipatti,which is located 14 kms away from the outskirts of salem near aathur. a 13 year old (8th grade) girl named rajalakshmi was beheaded by her neighbour dhinesh kumar the previous evening. she had allegedly spurned his advances. this happended when the #metoo campaigns were going viral,and yet nobody seemed to notice such incident.what happened was,she was sexually harassed by him previously.she even told this to her parents but they couldn't do anything as they were from a dalit family and he was from a dominant caste.that day,when chinnaponnu (rajalakshmi's mother) and rajalakshmi were stringing flowers,he came there with a sickle and beheaded her inspite of chinnaponnu's intervention.then he headed home with rajalakshmi's head where his wife sarada advised him to discard it elsewhere.subsequently, they went to police station together and surrendered.sarada convinced the police that he was mentally ill but it was just a ploy to save her husband.during investigation police made it clear that he was mentally and physically sound.they police see's this as a caste crime whereas the society see's this as a sex crime.in my opinion it's both,because he sexually assaulted her first and then he was enraged that a dalit woman had the audacity to spurn him.now he can be out on bail, which shouldn't be happening.in my opinion the case should be tried under posco act(death penalty).its a shame that we all failed to notice such a horrible incident.rape is a serious crime,i feel that the convicted rapist should experience consequences in keeping with the severity of their crime,not based on the privilege of their caste or the colour of their skin.women in india have always been worshipped as goddess and all the rapes, acid attacks and everything,all these has put us in shame.something has to be done to put an end to this cruelty.i hereby conclude that if we all join our hands together we might be able to put an end to this. #justiceforrajalakshmi #dailyart #acrylic #art #artsy
#painting #potrait

text:
i have finished the first batch of little reclaimed heart paintings and will be sharing details of them with you over the next couple of weeks. i created this series in response to my essay, "i was a promiscuous teen: an open letter to all the men from my past". in writing the letter, i have freed myself from the shame and fear that i have felt most of my life.  these paintings are my way of putting my broken heart back together.  join my arventure (link in bio) for early access to my december pop up shop where i'll have a selection of these for sale.

text: 8 november. the experts agree that i’ve been processing my trauma quite well but we’re looking for additional experts to sit at my table. we’re currently conducting a nationwide search for a provider that has experience working with an individual who has been raped in excess of 100 times. even better would be experience with someone who was drugged and raped, but that’s probably hoping for too much. for the people responsible for turning me into porn, you know not what you have awakened, and certainly not what i now remember.

text:
i've been catcalled and felt uncomfortable around men a ton, but i'm fortunate to have never been sexually assaulted or raped thus far in my life. that being said, i'm drawn to the space because, quite frankly, i'm shocked that i haven't been. the stats for the number of women (and men) that have been assaulted, and continue to be assaulted every day, are staggeringly high, but that doesn't even remotely take into account the blackouts and situations i used to put myself in when i was still drinking.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i certainly can't remember a lot of my drunken nights but i can remember two in particular where i thought it would be fun to pretend i was staying at a random hotel. i got past the front desk for both, took the elevator up to some random floor and started wandering the halls. i have one extremely vague memory that (i think) i knocked on a random hotel room door and then was standing inside the room by a window. i don't remember anyone else being there, and i know i left shortly after and somehow found my way to ny penn to catch a train home.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
another time i have a vague memory of drunkingly walking around jersey city by myself. two guys came out of a bar with another woman. in hindsight, i'm sure they were all just friends heading to their respective homes after a night out, but in that moment i feared for the woman's safety. i followed the group (i'm sure not discreetly) for awhile. my parents knew i was out alone and i was ignoring their worried calls. i finally let a friend pick me up.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
there are more stories of dangerous situations drunk me was in that i was extremely lucky to make it out of unscathed, but that's not the point. the point is that sexual assault is such a problem in this country (never mind the world). drunk women (and men) are prayed upon; sober women (and men) are preyed upon; kids are preyed upon; teens are preyed upon; adults are prayed upon. victims are all different and it's never their fault. we need to maintain this safe space for survivors, believe them, and to all do our part to stop all forms of assault and rape.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

you're a #chauvinist if you don't understand emotional abuse. you're not a #feminist, if you call something as a one time thing. if you want to become a good human being learn to accept your bad behaviours and work on it. don't call it just a 'reaction'. #metoo is a movement towards abuse, exploitation and violence don't tell a woman that "once im famous, you can #metoo about me and gain attention."
trust me, if you think a woman is sharing her story for attention then you're missing out on the awareness part. 
this movement isn't about victim playing but about finding our voices.
i'm not a victim and i'll never be one so i'm proud of my vulnerabilities, my emotional dependencies. you have no right to objectify such a phenomenal movement just cos you don't understand its importance. we are all feminist as long as no girl comes up to you and says, "u r my abuser." be a feminist accept your mistakes irrespective of your gender. respect others. :)

text:
[new research suggests that almost 9 percent of people in the united states have distress caused by difficulty controlling their sexual feelings, urges and behaviors.
#
but the gap between genders was very small: just over 10 percent of men showed compulsive sexual behavior, compared to 7 percent of women. "historically, it's been thought that compulsive sexual behaviors affect mostly men. 
#
but women are showing that they are experiencing difficulty controlling sexual urges and behavior, too," said study author janna dickenson. she is a postdoctoral fellow at the university of minnesota, in minneapolis.
#
dickenson explained that such behaviors can vary widely. "some people might masturbate excessively so that it interferes with the ability to work, or someone might be paying for sex so much that it's damaging financially," she explained, adding that sexual behaviors become a problem when they influence your life in a way that's destructive.
#
mental health professionals have long debated whether or not sexual addiction is an actual addiction or an impulse disorder. what is common to problematic sexual behavior, no matter how it is classified, is substantial difficulty controlling sexual feelings, urges and behaviors to the point that it causes distress and impairment.
#
using this definition, the study team asked more than 2,000 people to complete a screening test for compulsive sexual disorder. 8.6 percent of those screened were found to possibly have csbd.
#
dickenson said it's important to note that this study only used a screening tool. someone who tests positive on this test should be referred for further evaluation.]
♧

text:
dear washington
dear lawmakers
when will it stop?
when will these mass shootings come to an end? this is not about parties and division; this is about unity. uniting and coming together for the good of all people. we all know #mentalhealth is at the bottom of the list. why? please don’t say we have no money; by all the  money spend on hate  campaign commercials, we all know better. actions speak louder than words. for once, do something about it. one of my representatives, @drphilroe, carries the slogan, ‘people not politics’, then start proving this to the people. do something. do something now. start with practicing satya, especially you, #marshablackburn. try being the first female governor to increase #mentalhealthawareness and actually providing some kind of help. i now have to use the hashtag #metoo because of mental health. do something before another life is lost. any ugly comment will be deleted. #mentalhealth #ptsd 
#veterans #metoo #yoga #movement #mindfulness #workforchange #unity #satya

text:
glitch is an interactive sound & sculpture installation exploring the relationship between trauma and memory through touch, poetry, and compartmentalization.
▫
💚 ▫
the piece is comprised of 7 touch-sensitive orbs, each containing a small sculpture. when held, each orb triggers audio playback of a poem from the glitch poetry collection. ▫
💚 ▫
written 2017-18, the poems are each a personal reflection on intersections of intimacy, abuse, illness, and recovery. audio distortions emerge through audience interaction– as more orbs are held & poems overlap, distortions in the audio begin to emerge, imitating the dysfunction and dissonance that occur when the brain is exposed to repeated, compound trauma. ▫
💚 ▫
i am so grateful to everyone who has participated in this project. to bear witness / support my work please check out the link in my bio or go to heliotropism.bandcamp.com/releases ▫
💚 ▫
original photograph by bérengère marin-dubuard (edited & cropped for instagram) ▫

#repostsave @caforprogress with @repostsaveapp ・・・ join us today for the second annual #metoo survivors' march at hollywood and highland!
.
➡schedule
12-1pm opening speeches and performances
1-2pm we march 💥
2-3pm closing speeches and performances
.
me too march international is holding space today for the victims of the woolsey fire currently raging throughout ventura and los angeles counties, and the victims of the recent shooting at the borderline bar in thousand oaks. the victims are members of our communities. we recognize that the changing environmental conditions have caused disasters such as the fires to become increasingly worse and me too march international stands with all victims of natural disaster and climate change, recognizing that mass movement of people can often result in chaotic scenarios where people are victimized in various ways. in addition, me too march international recognizes that lax gun laws and lapses in mental health care have led to thousands of unnecessary gun deaths each year, and me too march international supports all efforts to expand mental health support.
.
today, we ask attendees to carry a white rose while we march, in order to symbolize our solidarity with the victims and our hope for a better future.
.

text:
take a chance to step outside of your comfort zone. try something different. can't hurt you to try, right? don't knock it if you haven't! we all live & learn in different ways! to find out what ways work for us, it doesn't normally come over night. self help doesn't have to be done over a break up or loss just to improve yourself as a person. if you strive to be a better person, your best self, you will try and do anything to achieve that.. at all times!! don't let anything or anyone get in your way of achieving that. if the people whom you have in your life aren't teaching you, supporting you and your dreams, or there giving you endless love then they have no need to be in your life! don't let toxic people get the best of you, give you bad energy and get you filled with depression/anger/anxiety. make clear boundaries, stick to your word & know your worth! don't hold on to the past. live in the day & for the future, let go of the pain and scars you hold hidden, deep inside. find a friend or a counselor, therapist. someone you can trust to open up to, to be able to let go. the pain, hurt & anger will set you free.. let your future be bright, it all starts within! 🌟

#selfhelp #changeishealthy #noexcuses #relief #weightlifted #therapy #biggerperson #letstalkaboutit #painisreal #mentalillness #mentaldisorders #metoo #geteducated #takentoolightly

.
.
.

text:
"hit me" by diane nguyen @dianesaurus
victims of sexual assault are often scared to come forward because of the criticism they might face. here's what visualist diane had to say about her piece. "the #metoo movement has been empowering for many, but on the flipside, it also brought out plenty of ugliness. these are various statements that get applied to every victim and it's a disparaging act that needs to stop. it sends the message that violation of a person's body without their permission is not only permissible, but its also his/her fault."

text:
when so many powerhouses grace the stage, you wonder it doesn’t collapse under the pressure of their magnificence. #facingrace saturday keynote tarana burke introduced by alicia garza and interviewed by linda sarsour. | “tarana burke shares the story behind the genesis of the viral 2017 time person of the year-winning ‘me too’ movement, and gives strength and healing to those who have experienced sexual trauma or harassment. 
the simple yet courageous #metoo hashtag campaign has emerged as a rallying cry for people everywhere who have survived sexual assault and sexual harassment – and tarana’s powerful, poignant story as creator of what is now an international movement that supports survivors will move, uplift, and inspire you. 
#metoo is not just an overnight hashtag sensation; tarana has dedicated more than 25 years of her life to social justice and to laying the groundwork for a movement that was initially created to help young women of color who survived sexual abuse and assault. the movement now inspires solidarity, amplifies the voices thousands of victims of sexual abuse, and puts the focus back on survivors. in her upcoming book, "where the light enters," tarana discusses the importance of the #metoo movement as well as her personal journey from "victim to survivor to thriver." a sexual assault survivor herself, tarana is now working under the banner of the ‘me too’ movement to assist other survivors and those who work to end sexual violence. she is also senior director of programs at brooklyn-based girls for gender equity. on stage, she provides words of empowerment that lift up marginalized voices, enables survivors across all races, genders, or classes to know that they are not alone, and creates a place for comfort and healing to those who have experienced trauma.” | #facingracekeynote #facingrace #facingrace2018 #raceforward #metoo #metoomovement #colorlines #racialequity #equity #racialjustice #justice #centerforsocialinclusion @taranajaneen @metoomvmt @chasinggarza @lsarsour @centerforsocialinclusion @raceforward @colorlinesnews

it's good to be like peter pan - no worries, no hassle, you play with friends all day long, you get into adventures and you do dirty tricks for pirates. and then you can go home, where the wonderful wendy will feed, wipe your nose, read a bedtime story and go to fix what you managed to destroy in a day. as forgiving perfect mom.
why are there peter pan! good to be like peter griffin. you can hijack a rocket, smash half the town and drag the horse home, and comfortable lois will grumble-grumble, but still fix everything and accept you with open arms, not forgetting to wear lace lingerie for your sake, even if you are a dumb guy with a certificate, cross yourself wider and regular farting your daughter in the face.
no matter how you are - even a superhero, even a genius-scientist, even a loser, even a crazy fool, she will still be there - an ideal human function created to collect the broken wood, to guide you on the right path when you walk up on the wrong paths, and in the end you get for good as a trophy for achievements.
approximately such a picture for girls and women emerges from the mass media - this amazing world, where there are one girl for ten guys. she has no personality, she has no friends, she hangs out only with the boys, her whole role is reduced to the function of mommy / nanny / teacher in the team, and, despite her overwhelming ideality, she sooner or later gets the protagonist, even if by itself a little smarter than mold. well, not a competent person to save the world and not equal to himself in the life mates to choose, what are you!

text:
part 2
here it is, discrimination against men: most of the directors, writers and producers who create those cartoons, movies, games, and so on, are men. they can cut funding for the animated series, because in the lead role the girl (hello, modern “nickelodeon”!), they can draw heroines with the same face, because otherwise they “will no longer be cute” (hello, modern “disney”!), “girly” projects can be canceled altogether, because “only boys buy toys and fan paraphernalia” (hello, “cartoon network”!) may demand to replace the main character with a hero in order to release the game (the authors of life is strange are good -sight), and when collecting statistics on the composition of the target audithory comics girls in the survey can be ignored altogether ("dc comics" - not a day without stupid actions). feminists have long struggled with this way of representing female images. with an endless succession of useless trophy princesses, empty-headed smurfett, public moms and idealized goddesses on a pedestal with which girls cannot associate themselves, because these images are not individual and do not develop from the beginning to the end of the work.
fighting gender stereotypes, because of which all films and cartoons as a blueprint.
they struggle with the unshakable dullness of studios, stubbornly ignoring the interests of 50% of the audience.

text: today @taranajaneen and i shared some healing and transformative space together. you may have just learned about tarana in the past year but she’s been working to protect defend and support black women and girls since she was 14 years old and founded the #metoo movement in 2006. we talked about being unapologetic in every space we are in and not allowing others to coopt our work or build off of our sacrifice. we speak truth and never back down to make any one feel comfortable. we live in a moment of crisis and it is women of color who are rising to the occasion. women of color are also the ones sacrificing the most for all of us and we must love and protect one another. today was full of healing and grateful for the love and support of our friends at @raceforward and @facingrace. i love you tarana and will follow you anywhere. #wocleadership #womenlead #followblackwomen #trustblackwomen #facingrace #facingrace2018

‌‎مافي اي اضرار جانبية بالمرة ‌‎مكونات المنتج:
‌‎١- الوفيرا جيل : ووظيفته التخلص من السموم بالجسم
‌‎وتهيئته لتخسيس الكرش
‌‎٢- فيلدز اوف قرينز : حبوب مكونة من مواد ١٠٠٪؜ طبيعية وهي المادة الفعالة لعملية التخسيس
‌‎٣- هيربل تي : شاي من الاعشاب الطبيعية يساعد علي حرق الدهون ‌‎موزع معتمد ***

text:
we would like to invite you to come see our play today at 8:00pm and tomorrow sunday at 3:00pm 
it is a experimental, avant garde and surreal performance. we use a combination of sounds, movement and music. citizens of the gray or this dark thing that sleeps in me is a theatrical production generated by the curiosity of how the relationship between man and woman has evolved throughout the years and how this relationship has become a struggle for power; a fight to death where there can be only one winner. 
the play portrays a world which is deeply correlated with the the #metoo movement!

there is no dialogue, nor text in this play. it traspases  language  barriers in such a way that any person from any country can understand it, given its universal codes.

at the theater for the new city, ny. 
dates: nov. 9th-25th
visit: https://bit.ly/2nfevgd to get your tickets now.
www.citizensofthegray.com

text:
mariska has taught me to be open, to be fearless & to be strong. .
.
.
today, nov 10th, something has happened to me which is part of a domestic violence/assault. i really can’t talk about it yet, but still i need to get it off my chest to let it “go”. i feel like what happened is my fault, and i could have protect myself.. i’m a mess now. .
.
.
yet i know i’m gonna survive this. i don’t know how, but i will. with @therealmariskahargitay in my mind i will. ❤️ i’d love to got some words of encouragement of you guys.. 💔

text:
the actions of cristian buitron are sickening and uncomfortably distressing. while i never experienced sexual assault in his presence, looking back there were warning signs of his true nature. hearing stories from other women has brought up painful memories of that inner voice in my head that i chose to ignore. and for that, i regret.
•
before i share my own story. i want to stress…. it is never the victim’s responsibility to explain or dissect and share their experience of sexual assault. i appreciate the bravery of every woman who has come forward. it takes an unimaginable amount of strength to do this. their words are powerful and have initiated opportunity for healing and change. but i also respect the choice of anyone to work through their experience in privacy with family, friends and therapy.
•
i knew cristian through the community. he shot with many of my friends and co-workers. he shot events at the studio i teach at. when he asked me to shoot it seemed like a normal progression. i assumed through the plethora of connections that he was to be trusted. he wanted to do a body paint shoot. i was not really interested in this. i didn’t find these images to be that appealing or the concept especially original. i would have preferred to just shoot fitness photos. but i figured since he was the photographer and i was not paying for the shoot that if i agreed to shoot, it would have to be in the direction of his vision.
•
so we arranged a shoot date. i cancelled the day before we were supposed to meet. i just had this bad feeling. we rescheduled. i let him know my reservations about the body paint aspect. he told me i could think about it and bring other clothing options to shoot in. he also told me to bring shoes i didn’t mind getting covered in paint in case i changed my mind about the body painting. (continued below) 
_______________________________________
#metoo

text:
gun control. a topic that is widely debated worldwide, especially in america -  a topic that gets brought up time and time again with little to no amendments being made, despite thousands being killed every year. in the uk we have had less than 50 massacres or mass killings since 61 ad - 28 of them done either with firearms or bombs. 
in contrast to this, the thousand oak mass shooting was the 307th mass shooting in america this year, with over 12000  victims losing their lives to firearms. the deaths of the 12000 americans this year impact not only the lives of the victims but also the lives of the families - 12000 human beings dead, likely many more than 100,000 humans effected terribly and irreversibly. 
all for what ? the president of the united states of america, donald trump, amongst many other leading politicians, accepts an absolutely colossal sum of money each year (some may call it bribery) from some of the biggest gun companies in the usa, mainly the national rifle association. this has to stop, it is so, so absurd that someone who has been accused  of sexual harassment, someone who wants to erase the rights of a group of people just because of their gender orientation and someone who cares more about money than the welfare of 'his' people is allowed to be the president . unfortunately, it is not something we can immediately change but trump making crude jokes about the deaths of people and giving those affected 'his prayers' is not enough . praying, despite it sometimes helping  the individual mentally, will not stop the shootings, nor will it bring those who have been brutally killed back . america, we beg you, please introduce gun control now, before yet more innocent people die . imagine if it was your kid that was killed whilst in school, an everyday thing where the biggest threat should be detention, because someone with a gun had killed them. would you want to change gun laws then, to stop other people's kids and families from being torn apart, or would you sit back, lap up the money you're being paid and say that it's ok because 'people have a right to bear arms' ? cont in comments .

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: love it or hate it, office politics is an inevitable part of organizational life. many people associate political behavior with backstabbing and manipulation — but there is a constructive side to being politically savvy. being able to negotiate, influence, engage, convince, and persuade others is how things get done in organizations — and how organizations decide what’s worth doing at all. developing political skill reduces stress and enhances performance, reputation, promotability, and career progression at work. a 2008 survey of 250 managers in the uk revealed that 90% of them believed that political skill is required to succeed and to improve one’s career prospects. this has been further supported by numerous research studies that make the case for engaging in office politics. while the link between political skill and career success is firmly established, there is a problem: office politics doesn’t work for everyone in the same way. research finds that it is a man made game that often marginalizes women and racial minorities. this is what my phd is investigating. to learn more please read my @harvard_business_review article ☝️link in bio 🙌 i would love to hear from each of you about your experiences with this 👇⭐️

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subve elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

pamela anderson says #metoo movement “paralyzes men:” "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger” -  blogged by: @raquelharristv (@60minutes)

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
ex-playmate #pamelaanderson is under fire after making controversial remarks about the #metoo movement. anderson discussed her thoughts on feminism during a “60 minutes australia” interview. while referring to her time modeling for “playboy,” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. "i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "i think this feminism can go too far – i'm a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore, i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i'm sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that."when asked about #harveryweinstein she highlighted specific lessons her mother taught her. "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it's supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. "you're talking about harvey weinstein?" the interviewer asked her. "yeah, i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go, in get the job," she said, laughing. "i'm canadian i'm going to speak my mind okay? i'm sorry, i'm sorry, i'm not politically correct, maybe." while her take may be somewhat opposite of the feminist movement, anderson has spoken out about issues that matter to women like the dangers of ridesharing apps and pornography. --------------------------------------------------#therealremyredd #blackmedia #bothervex  #blackinamerica  #blacklivesmatter  #blackhistoryiseveryday #blackhistory  #blackhistorymonth #stephcurry #lebron #nas #beyonce #beyoncé #kimkardashian #cardib  #nickiminaj  #worldstar #getthestrap #colinkaepernick #hiphop #nike #boycottnfl #cosby #billcosby #danielclary #danyejones

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
i never spent much time thinking about what life would be like after i left, because i never saw a way out. i was naive enough to think leaving would be the hardest part and once i did that everything would get easier. 🙄 if i had only known then what i know now. the effects of being in a long term dv relationship/marriage are lifelong. the damage is there. it is always there. with a lot of inner work, therapy and support things do get better. but you do leave forever changed. complex ptsd is not a joke. it's not an easy thing to learn to live with. i had a very busy week.  too busy infact. i had a lot of triggers and a few flashbacks.  like any illness or injury,  when you're tired your symptoms get worse. last night i was in tears. i can't even say why. it's just like my brain can only process so much and once i have reached my limit, i start shutting down,  checking out emotionally.  i just want to be alone. but i don't want to be alone. i can't process any more information.  noise, lights, temperature,  everything can bother me. usually when i get to this place i  tell my family my ptsd is triggered and my brain needs a break. unfortunately,  the rest of the world doesn't care if this is what's going on internally. i just look dramatic or lazy, attention seeking etc. in reality i am just trying to keep myself together.  some days are just hard. and sometimes it's everyday stress that is too overwhelming. i haven't been able to convince myself that i am  safe.... but then again, maybe it's because as long as he is out there, i am not.  so for tonight, i will do self care. tomorrow as well. letting myself have a break from my reality and just focus on getting through each moment. stay strong with me 💜

#whywomendontleave #domesticabuse #complexptsd #domesticviolence #dv #violenceagainstwomen #narcissist#overit #ptsd#staystrong#selfcare#breathe#itsokaytonotbeokay#menarevictimstoo#metoo#financialabuse#ptsdsurvivor #complexptsdawareness#compassion#strength#ifyouonlyknew

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
a new use case is emerging for cryptocurrency: helping women who've suffered sexual harassment or assault gain financial independence while also protecting their privacy.

case in point, a sexual assault survivor used the crypto-powered payment processor seeds to crowdfund $500 in september after the trauma left her unable to work for several months.

had she used a traditional crowdfunding site like kickstarter or gofundme, the survivor would have had to provide a government-issued id and bank account, which someone working at the platform might have connected with her story.

instead, using the seeds ethereum-based token allowed this first-time crypto user to raise the money without revealing her identity to anyone directly involved other than the platform's ceo, rachel cook.

the survivor received the token – which cost less than a quarter –as a gift from cook in order to post a "request for help" through 30 apps that use seeds' free front-end tools, such as aura, an app for meditation. users then donated through the in-app pop-up with their credit cards.

usually, that money is split between app developers, seeds' 10 percent cut, and the end-recipient who filed the request.

but in this case, cook waived all fees once the tokenized request was fulfilled. cook said it only took three weeks to raise the funds, the fastest fulfillment since the token was first launched in october 2017.
#blockchain #cryptocurrency #metoo

text:
a new use case is emerging for cryptocurrency: helping women who've suffered sexual harassment or assault gain financial independence while also protecting their privacy.

case in point, a sexual assault survivor used the crypto-powered payment processor seeds to crowdfund $500 in september after the trauma left her unable to work for several months.

had she used a traditional crowdfunding site like kickstarter or gofundme, the survivor would have had to provide a government-issued id and bank account, which someone working at the platform might have connected with her story.

instead, using the seeds ethereum-based token allowed this first-time crypto user to raise the money without revealing her identity to anyone directly involved other than the platform's ceo, rachel cook.

the survivor received the token – which cost less than a quarter –as a gift from cook in order to post a "request for help" through 30 apps that use seeds' free front-end tools, such as aura, an app for meditation. users then donated through the in-app pop-up with their credit cards.

usually, that money is split between app developers, seeds' 10 percent cut, and the end-recipient who filed the request.

but in this case, cook waived all fees once the tokenized request was fulfilled. cook said it only took three weeks to raise the funds, the fastest fulfillment since the token was first launched in october 2017.
#blockchain #cryptocurrency #metoo

text:
rp @whywomendontleave: i never spent much time thinking about what life would be like after i left, because i never saw a way out. i was naive enough to think leaving would be the hardest part and once i did that everything would get easier. 🙄 if i had only known then what i know now. the effects of being in a long term dv relationship/marriage are lifelong. the damage is there. it is always there. with a lot of inner work, therapy and support things do get better. but you do leave forever changed. complex ptsd is not a joke. it's not an easy thing to learn to live with. i had a very busy week. too busy infact. i had a lot of triggers and a few flashbacks. like any illness or injury, when you're tired your symptoms get worse. last night i was in tears. i can't even say why. it's just like my brain can only process so much and once i have reached my limit, i start shutting down, checking out emotionally. i just want to be alone. but i don't want to be alone. i can't process any more information. noise, lights, temperature, everything can bother me. usually when i get to this place i tell my family my ptsd is triggered and my brain needs a break. unfortunately, the rest of the world doesn't care if this is what's going on internally. i just look dramatic or lazy, attention seeking etc. in reality i am just trying to keep myself together. some days are just hard. and sometimes it's everyday stress that is too overwhelming. i haven't been able to convince myself that i am safe.... but then again, maybe it's because as long as he is out there, i am not. so for tonight, i will do self care. tomorrow as well. letting myself have a break from my reality and just focus on getting through each moment. stay strong with me 💜

a woman who outsmarts men in the 21st century: b*tch, assaulted.

|

and to women who do the same, or tag along with men like that? i hope very much that you either grow a brain, or find your comeuppance too.

text:
today i hiked up to 9999 ft to see this tree. it’s a bristlecone pine estimated to be 3500 years old. can you imagine what it’s seen. the changes in the world that have taken place while its roots grow deeper and branches continue to grow to the sky. the time i spent sitting on its roots made my life seem very impatient, like i’m moving through life too quickly. this tree has stood in the same place, felt the sunlight from the same angle, had the same view for 3500 years. why do i go through life so quickly? can i stop and enjoy the stillness? the light on my cheek? the breeze through the air? i’m grateful for this incredible tree. for all it taught me today. .
.
.
.

text:
people get so caught up in arguing that they miss the growing. .

have you ever heard ...”you are what you love and not what loves you?”
.

here’s what i mean by that, when you’re younger you spend your time doing everything that you love. whatever that is; dressing up like a superhero, drawing, singing, there’s no judgment and then we grow up, we allow other people to tell us who we are and what we should love. .

we want to be excepted so badly by other people that we start moving away from our true selves. .

and that my friends is why we live in a state of fear.  so now you end up  becoming dependent on external forces that you can’t control and then everything starts controlling you. .

when did you stop working on you?  the most successful people on this planet do not give a rats ass about what other people think of them, they spend their whole time working on themselves.  and that’s what makes them extraordinary.

and that’s what will make you extraordinary too!! know this, i’ll be one of your biggest cheerleaders because i believe in you!  cheers my friends!

text:

via @balleralert 
pamela anderson says #metoo movement “paralyzes men:” "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger” -  blogged by: @raquelharristv (@60minutes)
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
ex-playmate #pamelaanderson is under fire after making controversial remarks about the #metoo movement. anderson discussed her thoughts on feminism during a “60 minutes australia” interview. while referring to her time modeling for “playboy,” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. "i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "i think this feminism can go too far – i'm a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore, i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i'm sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that."when asked about #harveryweinstein she highlighted specific lessons her mother taught her. "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it's supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. "you're talking about harvey weinstein?" the interviewer asked her. "yeah, i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go, in get the job," she said, laughing. "i'm canadian i'm going to speak my mind okay? i'm sorry, i'm sorry, i'm not politically correct, maybe." while her take may be somewhat opposite of the feminist movement, anderson has spoken out about issues that matter to women like the dangers of ridesharing apps and pornography. --------------------------------------------------#therealremyredd #blackmedia #bothervex  #blackinamerica  #blacklivesmatter  #blackhistoryiseveryday #blackhistory  #blackhistorymonth #stephcurry #lebron #nas #beyonce #beyoncé #kimkardashian #cardib  #nickiminaj  #worldstar #getthestrap #colinkaepernick #hiphop #nike #boycottnfl #cosby #billcosby #danielclary #danyejones

ex-playmate #pamelaanderson is under fire after making controversial remarks about the #metoo movement. anderson discussed her thoughts on feminism during a “60 minutes australia” interview. while referring to her time modeling for “playboy,” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. "i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "i think this feminism can go too far – i am a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore, i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i am sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that."when asked about #harveryweinstein she highlighted specific lessons her mother taught her. "my mother taught me do not go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it is supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. "you are talking about harvey weinstein?" the interviewer asked her. "yeah, i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go, in get the job," she said, laughing. "i am canadian i am going to speak my mind okay? i am sorry, i am sorry, i am not politically correct, maybe." while her take may be somewhat opposite of the feminist movement, anderson has spoken out about issues that matter to women like the dangers of ridesharing apps and pornography. --------------------------------------------------#therealremyredd #blackmedia #bothervex  #blackinamerica  #blacklivesmatter  #blackhistoryiseveryday #blackhistory  #blackhistorymonth #stephcurry #lebron #nas #beyonce #beyoncé #kimkardashian #cardib  #nickiminaj  #worldstar #getthestrap #colinkaepernick #hiphop #nike #boycottnfl #cosby #billcosby #danielclary #danyejones

text:
the time i was sober for a session...
.
.
when i use to record before i was pretty much never sober.  it’s true 🤷🏽‍♂️. and that’s not a knock to those who do it before a session, it’s just that...i know why i use to do it.  i needed to conjure the courage, the bravado, the swag...but i was scared.  it’s funny cuz that was when i was doing a fully produced album with edits, multiple takes, and a whole lotta auto-tune lol.  and years later i’m here doing this unplugged album with one-take recordings and it’s like i’m completely naked in that booth lol. .
.
had a talk with my friend and engineer  @alaeddinmusic @granted.records and he said, being authentic and real with your music is sometimes the hardest and i think i have to agree.  i know it’s rewarding and freeing to be yourself and easier in the sense that you don’t have keep up this fake front and all that theory...but it is hella hard in practice.  but four tracks later i’m kinda’ proud of the work we put in...and yea it was hella hard, and scary, and a little emotional and physically draining...but i realize i wasn’t sober for this session either.  cuz when you’re doing your passion and you’re literally pouring yourself into it there can be nothing more spiritual, more inspiring, and nothing more intoxicating 💜💫🌟.
.
.

tied up published in @ferocemagazine ⚡️.
•
'tied up' is a statement about humanity, our diversity and many ranges of our emotions. 
one of the qualities that make us sentient is the society we have built and the web of relationships we are a part of. we try to find balance in ourselves and in our relationships. 
moments of bliss, clarity and togetherness punctuated by moments of struggle and confusion, we are all essentially tied up together.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn
